WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:00.901 --> 00:00:05.202
<i>♪♪ [Seasonal]</i>

2
00:00:05.272 --> 00:00:07.537
<i>[House] We are
condemned to useless labor.</i>

3
00:00:07.608 --> 00:00:09.543
<i>Fourth circle of hell.</i>

4
00:00:09.610 --> 00:00:13.411
<i>Charting goes a lot faster when
you eliminate all classic poetry.</i>

5
00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:16.882
<i>Writing down what we already
know to be read by nobody.</i>

6
00:00:16.950 --> 00:00:19.784
I'm pretty sure Dante would
agree that qualifies as useless.

7
00:00:19.853 --> 00:00:21.913
You're over two weeks
behind in your charting.

8
00:00:23.457 --> 00:00:26.359
Oops. I missed.

9
00:00:26.426 --> 00:00:29.419
- What are you. eight?
- Could an eight-year-old do this?

10
00:00:30.464 --> 00:00:33.059
You'd better stop.
or it'll stick that way.

11
00:00:33.133 --> 00:00:37.571
- You have a patient in Exam One.
- Yeah. but. see. I'm off at 12:00.
and it's already five of.

12
00:00:37.638 --> 00:00:41.097
<i>She's been waiting
for you since 1 1:00.</i>

13
00:00:43.877 --> 00:00:48.815
Melancholy without
hope. Which circle is that?

14
00:00:54.054 --> 00:00:56.489
Hi. I'm Dr. House.

15
00:00:56.557 --> 00:01:00.756
<i>What seems to be the problem?</i>
Show him your hands. Augustine.

16
00:01:07.234 --> 00:01:11.501
- It-It looks like stigmata.
- Shah. Pius.

17
00:01:11.572 --> 00:01:15.168
<i>You must be all the talk
around the "holy water" cooler.</i>

18
00:01:15.242 --> 00:01:18.406
<i>Been washing a lot of dishes
recently?</i> I help out in the kitchen.

19
00:01:18.478 --> 00:01:22.506
- Anything new in the kitchen?
- We just got a donation
of saucepans and pots this week.

20
00:01:22.583 --> 00:01:24.000
I unpacked and washed them.

21
00:01:24.024 --> 00:01:27.453
Should have spent your time
saving souls. It's easier on the hands.

22
00:01:27.521 --> 00:01:30.753
This is contact dermatitis.
You're allergic to dish soap.

23
00:01:30.824 --> 00:01:35.421
Nonsense. We've always used that
soap. Why is there a problem now?

24
00:01:35.495 --> 00:01:37.398
I've been a doctor for
years. Why do I have to

25
00:01:37.422 --> 00:01:39.432
keep assuring people
that I know what I'm doing?

26
00:01:39.499 --> 00:01:41.934
<i>A person can become
allergic to substances...</i>

27
00:01:42.002 --> 00:01:44.335
that they've had repeated
and prolonged exposure to.

28
00:01:45.906 --> 00:01:48.899
The good news is—free samples.

29
00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:52.939
Diphenhydramine.
It's an antihistamine.

30
00:01:53.013 --> 00:01:55.778
It'll stop the
allergic reaction.

31
00:01:55.849 --> 00:01:59.377
Take one every eight hours. It
might make you feel a little sleepy.

32
00:01:59.453 --> 00:02:03.015
<i>And get some of that over-the-counter
cortisone cream.</i> Thank you. Doctor.

33
00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:05.389
You want some
water? I have some tea.

34
00:02:05.459 --> 00:02:09.157
Well. you just relax for a few
minutes. That stuff works pretty fast.

35
00:02:14.935 --> 00:02:18.394
<i>♪♪ [Continues]</i>
Still out by 12:00.

36
00:02:18.472 --> 00:02:22.239
How do you solve a problem
like dermatitis? What?

37
00:02:22.309 --> 00:02:25.837
<i>Doctor? I want to thank
you for your patience.</i>

38
00:02:25.912 --> 00:02:30.577
She talkin' to you? I don't know.
She's certainly looking at me.

39
00:02:30.651 --> 00:02:34.053
<i>Ah. it's good to get
a secular diagnosis.</i>

40
00:02:34.121 --> 00:02:38.183
The sisters tend to interpret their
illnesses as divine intervention.

41
00:02:38.258 --> 00:02:41.023
And you don't? Then you're
wearing an awfully funny hat.

42
00:02:41.094 --> 00:02:43.654
<i>Ooh. boy. Excuse me.</i>

43
00:02:43.730 --> 00:02:47.360
If I break my leg. I believe
it happened for a reason.

44
00:02:47.434 --> 00:02:49.426
I believe God wanted
me to break my leg.

45
00:02:49.503 --> 00:02:52.735
I also believe he wants
me to put a cast on it.

46
00:02:52.806 --> 00:02:54.741
<i>Doctor! Something’s wrong.</i>

47
00:02:54.808 --> 00:02:57.937
[Wheezing. Gasping]

48
00:03:04.918 --> 00:03:08.446
Lift up your chin.

49
00:03:08.522 --> 00:03:11.549
Sister. you're having an
asthma attack. I need you to relax.

50
00:03:11.625 --> 00:03:14.561
Roll up her sleeve. please.
I'm gonna give you epinephrine.

51
00:03:14.628 --> 00:03:15.804
[Wheezing. Gasping Continue]

52
00:03:15.828 --> 00:03:17.628
It'll open your lungs
and help you breathe.

53
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:25.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

54
00:03:31.778 --> 00:03:35.374
[Wheezing. Gasping Subside]

55
00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:39.577
<i>What happened?</i>
Did she take the pill?

56
00:03:39.653 --> 00:03:42.748
<i>- Yes.</i>
- It's probably an allergic reaction.

57
00:03:42.823 --> 00:03:45.486
She's allergic to an
anti-allergy medicine?

58
00:03:45.559 --> 00:03:47.551
You figure somebody's
out to get her?

59
00:03:47.627 --> 00:03:49.562
- How are you feeling?
- [Quietly] Better.

60
00:03:49.629 --> 00:03:52.724
I'll put you on some
steroids instead.

61
00:03:52.799 --> 00:03:54.633
Is my heart supposed
to be feeling so funny?

62
00:03:54.657 --> 00:03:55.667
It's called adrenaline.

63
00:03:55.736 --> 00:03:58.968
- It makes your heart beat fast.
- [Rapid Heartbeat]

64
00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:02.009
- But not this fast.
- [Gasps]

65
00:04:02.075 --> 00:04:06.103
Get a nurse. please. Hold on.

66
00:04:06.179 --> 00:04:08.671
Help! Somebody help us!

67
00:04:12.018 --> 00:04:15.182
Somebody get in here!

68
00:04:16.389 --> 00:04:19.188
Call a code and charge up a
defibrillator. She's got no pulse.

69
00:05:06.973 --> 00:05:09.442
<i>[Nuns Murmuring]</i>

70
00:05:17.184 --> 00:05:20.263
<i>[Cuddy] You diagnosed the patient with
allergies and prescribed antihistamine.</i>

71
00:05:20.287 --> 00:05:23.257
She went into
respiratory distress.

72
00:05:23.323 --> 00:05:26.122
and you injected
her with epinephrine.

73
00:05:26.193 --> 00:05:28.287
Presumably 1 c.c.

74
00:05:28.361 --> 00:05:32.196
.1 c.c. That is the standard
dose. That is what I gave her.

75
00:05:32.265 --> 00:05:34.343
People don't go into cardiac
arrest from .1 c.c. epinephrine.

76
00:05:34.367 --> 00:05:37.680
<i>She must have a preexisting heart condition
that got exacerbated by the epinephrine.</i>

77
00:05:37.704 --> 00:05:39.682
It's too bad you didn't
make a notation in the chart.

78
00:05:39.706 --> 00:05:41.641
I can make it up right now.

79
00:05:41.708 --> 00:05:44.620
<i>The drawer has syringes with both dosages.
You could have reached for the wrong—</i>

80
00:05:44.644 --> 00:05:47.079
- But I didn't.
- Everyone makes mistakes.

81
00:05:47.147 --> 00:05:49.258
This is why doctors pay through
the nose for malpractice insurance.

82
00:05:49.282 --> 00:05:51.808
Relax. They're not gonna sue.

83
00:05:51.885 --> 00:05:54.081
The worst they'd do is
whack my hand with a ruler.

84
00:05:54.154 --> 00:05:57.600
- And the discipline board—
are they gonna whack your hand too?
- You're gonna report me?

85
00:05:57.624 --> 00:06:01.322
- What choice do I have?
- Uh. how about <i>not</i> report me?

86
00:06:03.997 --> 00:06:07.957
I can justify keeping her
here for a 24-hour observation.

87
00:06:08.034 --> 00:06:10.713
If you haven't found an underlying
cause for the cardiac arrest by then.

88
00:06:10.737 --> 00:06:12.672
I will have to
notify our attorneys.

89
00:06:19.346 --> 00:06:21.178
<i>[Cameron] Her hands
were red and swollen.</i>

90
00:06:21.248 --> 00:06:24.582
<i>Maybe she has a skin infection. Cellulitis?
That could manifest with tachycardia.</i>

91
00:06:24.651 --> 00:06:27.951
There's no history of fever. Results from
the C.B.C. didn't indicate an infection.

92
00:06:28.021 --> 00:06:29.959
<i>The eosinophils are mildly
elevated. Sed rate's up a</i>

93
00:06:29.983 --> 00:06:32.134
<i>bit. Could we be looking at
a systemic allergic response?</i>

94
00:06:32.158 --> 00:06:34.758
It's not allergic. Allergies don't
cause cardiac arrest like this.

95
00:06:34.828 --> 00:06:39.266
- Could be inflammation of the blood vessels.
- Vasculitis? That wouldn't give you
an elevated eosinophil count.

96
00:06:39.332 --> 00:06:41.130
Churg-Strauss vasculitis would.

97
00:06:41.201 --> 00:06:43.864
The blood vessels of the heart.
lungs and skin become inflamed.

98
00:06:43.937 --> 00:06:47.874
causing the asthma. rash and heart
problems—covers all her symptoms.

99
00:06:47.941 --> 00:06:50.274
You need a biopsy to diagnose.
Chest C.T. would be quicker.

100
00:06:50.343 --> 00:06:53.279
The lady just
came in with a rash.

101
00:06:53.346 --> 00:06:55.281
What the hell are those?

102
00:06:55.348 --> 00:06:57.283
Candy canes.

103
00:06:57.350 --> 00:07:01.048
Candy <i>canes?</i> Are you mocking me?

104
00:07:01.121 --> 00:07:04.990
<i>No. It-It's Christmas. and I—</i>

105
00:07:05.058 --> 00:07:08.825
I thought— Relax. It's a joke.

106
00:07:08.895 --> 00:07:10.940
[Foreman] Isn't the prognosis
for Churg-Strauss a bit grim?

107
00:07:10.964 --> 00:07:15.163
Yeah. Untreated. only 33%
of patients survive past a year.

108
00:07:15.235 --> 00:07:18.728
Treated—five years. Then I
definitely suggest treatment.

109
00:07:18.805 --> 00:07:21.217
If it was any other attending doctor.
I'd say that he made a mistake...

110
00:07:21.241 --> 00:07:23.176
and gave her too
much epinephrine.

111
00:07:23.243 --> 00:07:26.042
Saying you wouldn't
say it was my mistake...

112
00:07:26.112 --> 00:07:28.206
is saying it was my mistake.

113
00:07:29.282 --> 00:07:31.717
Everyone screws up. Your rule.

114
00:07:31.785 --> 00:07:34.050
I think you fit within the
subset of "everyone."

115
00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:36.089
I didn't screw up.

116
00:07:36.156 --> 00:07:41.254
- Order a chest C.T. and start the sister
on prednisone—40 milligrams T.I.D.
- The sister?

117
00:07:41.328 --> 00:07:45.925
Oh. didn't I mention? The
patient's a nun—Sister Augustine.

118
00:07:45.999 --> 00:07:48.525
[Moans] I hate nuns.

119
00:07:50.370 --> 00:07:52.339
Who doesn't?

120
00:07:55.575 --> 00:08:00.775
<i>♪♪ [Upbeat]</i>

121
00:08:04.317 --> 00:08:07.549
<i>- [Cameron]Sister Augustine?</i>
- We weren't watching.

122
00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:11.182
<i>[TV Turns Off]</i> We were trying
to see if this is the bed control.

123
00:08:11.257 --> 00:08:13.351
Oh. Uh. this one's
the bed control.

124
00:08:13.426 --> 00:08:15.918
And that's the TV control.

125
00:08:15.996 --> 00:08:19.296
I'm Dr. Cameron. This is
Dr. Chase and Dr. Foreman.

126
00:08:19.366 --> 00:08:22.234
I haven't seen television
in over 20 years.

127
00:08:22.302 --> 00:08:24.134
Do you consider it
the work of the devil.

128
00:08:24.204 --> 00:08:26.400
or do you just not get
cable where you live?

129
00:08:27.374 --> 00:08:30.071
- Um— - How are
you feeling. Sister?

130
00:08:30.143 --> 00:08:32.544
<i>I seem to be a little better.
They gave me some medication.</i>

131
00:08:32.612 --> 00:08:35.047
<i>Prednisone. It's a steroid
to help with the inflammation.</i>

132
00:08:35.115 --> 00:08:37.550
Has Dr. House
figured out what I have?

133
00:08:37.617 --> 00:08:39.745
Will I be okay? We're
not sure what's wrong yet.

134
00:08:39.819 --> 00:08:42.948
You'll have a chest C.T. scan this
afternoon that'll help with the diagnosis.

135
00:08:43.023 --> 00:08:46.187
<i>Dr. House is giving her medication.
and he doesn't know what she has yet?</i>

136
00:08:46.259 --> 00:08:49.661
<i>Trust. Sister Pius. It
all happens for a reason.</i>

137
00:08:49.729 --> 00:08:51.755
<i>[Foreman] He doesn't
know what he's doing.</i>

138
00:08:51.831 --> 00:08:54.801
The only problem that woman has is
that House grabbed the wrong syringe.

139
00:08:54.868 --> 00:08:59.067
You don't trust him? I don't trust a
man who won't admit he might be wrong.

140
00:08:59.139 --> 00:09:00.736
I notice you weren't
so quick to tell her she's

141
00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.518
got Churg-Strauss and
only has a couple years left.

142
00:09:02.542 --> 00:09:04.553
I don't tell patients bad
news unless it's conclusive.

143
00:09:04.577 --> 00:09:06.512
Because you know
he might be wrong.

144
00:09:06.579 --> 00:09:08.912
About Churg-Strauss. Not
about what happened in the clinic.

145
00:09:08.982 --> 00:09:12.419
[Scoffs] What about you. Chase?
You think he's infallible too?

146
00:09:12.485 --> 00:09:14.692
All I know is. if House
didn't make a mistake

147
00:09:14.716 --> 00:09:16.650
and Sister Augustine
has Churg-Strauss.

148
00:09:16.723 --> 00:09:19.625
he'll be self-satisfied and our
lives will be good for a few weeks.

149
00:09:19.692 --> 00:09:21.603
If House did make a
mistake. he'll be upset

150
00:09:21.627 --> 00:09:23.561
and our lives will be
miserable for months.

151
00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:25.758
[Chuckles] There is that.

152
00:09:25.832 --> 00:09:27.346
If Cuddy thinks I made
a mistake. the least

153
00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:28.944
she could do is suspend
me from clinic duty.

154
00:09:28.968 --> 00:09:31.802
She doesn't confuse making a
mistake with being incompetent.

155
00:09:31.871 --> 00:09:34.340
Oh. here we go—lesson time.

156
00:09:35.475 --> 00:09:38.274
I recognize that confidence
is not my short suit.

157
00:09:38.344 --> 00:09:41.075
I also recognize that I am
human and capable of error.

158
00:09:41.147 --> 00:09:44.140
So you might have
screwed this up? No.

159
00:09:44.217 --> 00:09:47.619
So it's merely a theoretical
capacity for error. Good point.

160
00:09:47.687 --> 00:09:50.282
Maybe there isn't one.
Maybe that's my error.

161
00:09:50.356 --> 00:09:53.636
Most people who think as much of themselves
as you do like to talk about themselves.

162
00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:57.392
Most people don't like to listen.
So. what's wrong with you?

163
00:10:05.305 --> 00:10:07.638
[Sniffing]

164
00:10:07.707 --> 00:10:11.166
Let me guess—inflammatory bowel.

165
00:10:11.244 --> 00:10:15.011
[Sighs] Wow. Yeah.
Is it that bad? <i>Yes.</i>

166
00:10:15.081 --> 00:10:18.449
It's also written on your chart.

167
00:10:18.518 --> 00:10:20.749
"Bloody diarrhea. gas. pain.

168
00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:22.846
Took sulfasalazine.
but it didn't work."

169
00:10:22.922 --> 00:10:26.017
- No. Then-Then I— -
"Next. tried steroid enemas.

170
00:10:26.092 --> 00:10:29.085
<i>Oral corticosteroids—
5-A.S.A.. 6-mercaptopurine."</i>

171
00:10:29.162 --> 00:10:31.358
- I'm impressed.
- By my medical history?

172
00:10:31.431 --> 00:10:33.900
By how well your
last doctor charted.

173
00:10:33.967 --> 00:10:36.334
It's one thing to have to go
to the bathroom every hour.

174
00:10:36.402 --> 00:10:39.236
but when the kids
sit on my lap. it's...

175
00:10:39.305 --> 00:10:41.399
<i>The store sent me home.
They're gonna fire me.</i>

176
00:10:41.474 --> 00:10:44.444
Can't you put me back on 5-A.S.A.?
Maybe it'll work this time. <i>Not likely.</i>

177
00:10:44.511 --> 00:10:48.278
I'm giving you a prescription.
It's cheap. which is good.

178
00:10:48.348 --> 00:10:50.283
because your insurance
company won't pay for it.

179
00:10:57.957 --> 00:11:01.359
- "Cogaritis"?
- Cigarettes.

180
00:11:01.427 --> 00:11:03.396
One twice a day.
No more. no less.

181
00:11:03.463 --> 00:11:05.864
<i>Studies have shown
that cigarette smoking...</i>

182
00:11:05.932 --> 00:11:08.595
is one of the most effective ways
to control inflammatory bowel.

183
00:11:08.668 --> 00:11:12.036
<i>Plus it's been well established
that you look 30% cooler.</i>

184
00:11:12.105 --> 00:11:15.564
- Are you kidding me?
- About the looking cooler. yeah.

185
00:11:15.642 --> 00:11:18.407
- The rest is true.
- Isn't it addictive and dangerous?

186
00:11:18.478 --> 00:11:22.210
Pretty much all the drugs I
prescribe are addictive and dangerous.

187
00:11:22.282 --> 00:11:24.877
The only difference with this
one is it's completely legal.

188
00:11:26.519 --> 00:11:28.988
Merry Christmas.

189
00:11:29.055 --> 00:11:32.787
<i>[Sister Augustine] I was talking to
the nurse— Arsenio. Do you know him?</i>

190
00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:37.024
Not really. He can take
pictures with his phone.

191
00:11:37.096 --> 00:11:40.555
Cool. That woman from
the lab was interesting too.

192
00:11:40.633 --> 00:11:43.762
She studied astrophysics
before becoming a nurse.

193
00:11:43.836 --> 00:11:47.796
You know the staff better than I
do. I love to hear all about people.

194
00:11:47.874 --> 00:11:51.003
- Yet you live in a monastery.
- It's where I serve our Lord
and the world best.

195
00:11:51.077 --> 00:11:54.844
Our Lord maybe. The rest of
the world. on the other hand.

196
00:11:54.914 --> 00:11:58.681
- would probably get more out of feeding
the homeless or— - Healing the sick?

197
00:11:58.751 --> 00:12:02.711
As an example. yeah. <i>Did
you always want to be a doctor?</i>

198
00:12:02.789 --> 00:12:06.851
Always. You always want to be a
nun? <i>My parents died when I was six.</i>

199
00:12:06.926 --> 00:12:10.556
I was raised in a foster
home run by the Church.

200
00:12:10.630 --> 00:12:14.658
When I was 18. I went to the monastery.
where they let me take my vows.

201
00:12:14.734 --> 00:12:17.932
<i>I've known no other life.
and I haven't wanted to.</i>

202
00:12:18.004 --> 00:12:21.532
<i>[Foreman On Speaker] Okay. Sister.
We need you to lie as still as possible.</i>

203
00:12:21.608 --> 00:12:23.600
<i>If you get scared.
just let us know.</i>

204
00:12:23.676 --> 00:12:26.475
As Jonah said from
inside the whale.

205
00:12:26.546 --> 00:12:30.813
<i>"When I had lost all hope. I
turned my thoughts to the Lord."</i>

206
00:12:30.883 --> 00:12:34.445
- Well. she's got God on her side.
<i>- [Cameron] I don't believe in God.</i>

207
00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:36.006
You're not even a
little agnostic? [Sister

208
00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:37.900
<i>[Augustine On Speaker] Is
it supposed to smell funny?</i>

209
00:12:37.924 --> 00:12:41.827
Someone ralphed in there this
morning. We cleaned it up. but...

210
00:12:41.894 --> 00:12:44.974
It's normal. Sister. It's
just a few more minutes.

211
00:12:44.998 --> 00:12:45.296
Mm.

212
00:12:45.365 --> 00:12:48.494
I believe in a higher order
that's in control of what happens.

213
00:12:48.568 --> 00:12:51.367
<i>but not one. anthropomorphic
entity called "God"...</i>

214
00:12:51.437 --> 00:12:53.682
that's concerned with the
everyday workings of you and me.

215
00:12:53.706 --> 00:12:56.471
What else is there to control but
the everyday workings of you and me?

216
00:12:56.542 --> 00:12:58.511
It's always about you. Foreman.

217
00:12:58.578 --> 00:13:00.422
What are you talking
about— The trees. the fish?

218
00:13:00.446 --> 00:13:02.458
<i>Should they be the ones
that think it's all about them?</i>

219
00:13:02.482 --> 00:13:04.542
<i>What about you. Chase?
Do you believe in God?</i>

220
00:13:06.686 --> 00:13:11.056
I believe Sister Augustine has no vascular
pathology. which means no Churg-Strauss.

221
00:13:11.124 --> 00:13:13.525
Which means House made a
mistake. No. not necessarily.

222
00:13:13.593 --> 00:13:17.394
It could be something else— thyrotoxicosis
or a carcinoid. I don't get you.

223
00:13:17.463 --> 00:13:21.195
You don't believe in God. but you're
willing to put complete faith in one man?

224
00:13:21.267 --> 00:13:24.601
<i>[Sister Augustine] Please. The
smell.</i> Let's get her out of there.

225
00:13:26.139 --> 00:13:28.108
[Gasping] I'm coming.
Sister. I gotcha.

226
00:13:28.174 --> 00:13:30.609
[Gasping] Please.
The smell. I'm comin'.

227
00:13:30.677 --> 00:13:32.908
I'm gonna be sick.
There's no smell.

228
00:13:32.979 --> 00:13:38.247
No. God. Oh! It’s
Jesus. It’s Jesus!

229
00:13:38.318 --> 00:13:40.753
[Crying] He's coming for me!

230
00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:43.289
He's burning me with his touch!

231
00:13:43.356 --> 00:13:45.222
Let's get her on some Ativan.

232
00:13:45.291 --> 00:13:49.126
The smells. religious visions— It's
symptomatic of temporal lobe swelling.

233
00:13:49.195 --> 00:13:51.790
- We don't want her
to— - She's seizing.

234
00:13:51.864 --> 00:13:54.561
- Jaw block!
- Help me get her on her side.

235
00:13:57.003 --> 00:14:00.269
- Religious visions?
- Yeah. And next comes...

236
00:14:07.413 --> 00:14:09.814
Patient tested positive
for herpetic encephalitis.

237
00:14:09.882 --> 00:14:12.482
- What's that tell us?
- Her immune system
is severely compromised.

238
00:14:12.518 --> 00:14:16.080
Oh. I know. Prednisone
compromises the immune system.

239
00:14:16.155 --> 00:14:21.423
- Isn't that the medicine that you gave her
for that thing she doesn't have?
- Yeah. that— Hey.

240
00:14:21.494 --> 00:14:25.659
- I'm thinking that's a trick question.
- Her immune system
is severely compromised.

241
00:14:25.732 --> 00:14:28.077
Two doses of prednisone
wouldn't do that.

242
00:14:28.101 --> 00:14:30.636
Are you hanging your
diagnosis on an adverb?

243
00:14:30.703 --> 00:14:35.732
- In 10 seconds. I'm going to announce that
I gave her the wrong dose in the clinic.
- You're gonna admit negligence?

244
00:14:35.808 --> 00:14:38.801
Unless you leave the room. If
you stay. you'll have to testify.

245
00:14:38.878 --> 00:14:42.406
Five. four.

246
00:14:42.482 --> 00:14:45.077
three. two...

247
00:14:45.151 --> 00:14:47.120
So. there I was
in the clinic. drunk.

248
00:14:47.186 --> 00:14:49.246
[Laughs] <i>I opened the
drawer. closed my eyes.</i>

249
00:14:49.322 --> 00:14:51.484
<i>take the first
syringe I can find—</i>

250
00:14:53.359 --> 00:14:56.193
So. what are the options for a
compromised immune system?

251
00:14:56.262 --> 00:14:58.804
Mixed connective tissue
disease. It'd explain

252
00:14:58.828 --> 00:15:01.394
why she was feeling
better on the prednisone.

253
00:15:01.467 --> 00:15:04.494
Sure. She was feeling better right
up to the moment it almost killed her.

254
00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:07.267
<i>On the other hand. it
explains the symptoms—</i>

255
00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:09.866
Swollen hands. pulmonary
problems. cardiac problems.

256
00:15:09.942 --> 00:15:11.843
<i>It all fits.</i> Except her
A.N.A. was normal.

257
00:15:11.911 --> 00:15:14.642
- So redraw the blood.
- But the treatment is corticosteroids...

258
00:15:14.714 --> 00:15:16.992
Prednisone—and we can't go
there because of the encephalitis.

259
00:15:17.016 --> 00:15:19.078
Then we'll treat it with
something that modulates

260
00:15:19.102 --> 00:15:20.976
the immune system
but doesn't suppress it...

261
00:15:21.053 --> 00:15:23.852
Hyperbaric oxygen chamber.

262
00:15:23.923 --> 00:15:26.049
There's no protocol
for putting a patient in a

263
00:15:26.073 --> 00:15:28.691
high-pressure oxygen room
to treat auto-immune problems.

264
00:15:28.761 --> 00:15:31.128
Oh. you people. Always
with the protocols.

265
00:15:32.598 --> 00:15:36.330
Prep the nun and
discontinue the prednisone.

266
00:15:41.908 --> 00:15:45.003
I am both amused and annoyed...

267
00:15:45.077 --> 00:15:47.569
that you think I should be
less stubborn than you are.

268
00:15:49.015 --> 00:15:52.247
You are aware of the
Hippocratic oath. right?

269
00:15:52.318 --> 00:15:54.405
The one that starts.
"First. do no harm." then

270
00:15:54.429 --> 00:15:56.585
goes on to tell us no
abortions. no seductions.

271
00:15:56.656 --> 00:15:59.353
and definitely no cutting of those
who labor beneath the stone?

272
00:15:59.425 --> 00:16:01.360
Yeah. I took a read
once. Wasn't impressed.

273
00:16:01.427 --> 00:16:05.489
Hyperbaric treatments could cause
oxygen toxicity—lung and eye damage.

274
00:16:05.565 --> 00:16:08.057
Every treatment has its dangers.
Which is why we only treat...

275
00:16:08.134 --> 00:16:10.763
if we're convinced the patient
actually needs the treatment.

276
00:16:10.837 --> 00:16:13.500
I'm convinced. You're not.

277
00:16:14.707 --> 00:16:17.040
Question is. what are you
gonna do about it? Hmm?

278
00:16:20.112 --> 00:16:23.173
I have an opening Thursday
at 3:00. Do you have a fourth?

279
00:16:24.183 --> 00:16:26.846
Is he any good? <i>[Door Opens]</i>

280
00:16:26.919 --> 00:16:28.911
Can I call you right back? Okay.

281
00:16:30.823 --> 00:16:32.815
What's up?

282
00:16:35.761 --> 00:16:39.596
[Chase] The pressure will force the oxygen
into your system. saturate your blood.

283
00:16:39.665 --> 00:16:42.726
<i>It will enhance white cell
activity. reduce the inflammation.</i>

284
00:16:42.802 --> 00:16:45.931
And that will help with this
mixed connective tissue disease?

285
00:16:46.005 --> 00:16:49.169
<i>We'll be doing about 10
treatments. and then we'll reevaluate.</i>

286
00:16:49.242 --> 00:16:52.610
<i>[Sister Augustine] The last treatment
with prednisone caused the seizures. right?</i>

287
00:16:52.678 --> 00:16:56.547
How confident is
Dr. House about this?

288
00:16:56.616 --> 00:16:59.416
<i>[Cameron] That you reacted so
strongly to the prednisone let us know...</i>

289
00:16:59.452 --> 00:17:01.597
that you had an underlying
problem with your immune system.

290
00:17:01.621 --> 00:17:05.080
<i>I guess it was a
blessing... of sorts.</i>

291
00:17:09.495 --> 00:17:12.158
[Man On TV] So. who's your
favorite reindeer. Nurse Arnold?

292
00:17:12.231 --> 00:17:14.166
Rudolph. I would've
thought it was Vixen.

293
00:17:14.233 --> 00:17:17.601
What are you implying? Nothing.

294
00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:20.299
<i>But I saw you at the
Christmas party with Dr. Riles...</i>

295
00:17:20.373 --> 00:17:22.808
<i>and Dr. Jorkins
and Nurse Crandall.</i>

296
00:17:22.875 --> 00:17:24.901
<i>[Nurse] I was just doing
some Christmas dancing.</i>

297
00:17:24.977 --> 00:17:29.472
- This is a chapel. a house of prayer.
<i>- [TV Continues. Indistinct]</i>

298
00:17:29.549 --> 00:17:31.677
House of prayer? Huh.

299
00:17:31.751 --> 00:17:33.686
That explains the
good reception.

300
00:17:33.753 --> 00:17:36.814
Also why nobody's ever here.

301
00:17:38.925 --> 00:17:41.019
I need to talk with
you. Dr. House.

302
00:17:41.093 --> 00:17:44.222
Sister Augustine believes
in things that aren't real.

303
00:17:45.531 --> 00:17:47.796
I thought that was a job
requirement for you people.

304
00:17:47.867 --> 00:17:52.362
She's been known
to lie to get sympathy.

305
00:17:52.438 --> 00:17:54.703
She's a hypochondriac.

306
00:17:54.774 --> 00:17:58.734
So you're warning me that I may
be treating a nonexistent ailment.

307
00:17:58.811 --> 00:18:01.303
Sore throats. joint pains.

308
00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:04.248
There's always something wrong.
and there's never a reason for it.

309
00:18:04.317 --> 00:18:06.343
Mother Superior
plays right into it...

310
00:18:06.419 --> 00:18:09.116
Lets Augustine off work duties.

311
00:18:09.188 --> 00:18:11.953
treating her as
fragile. special.

312
00:18:12.024 --> 00:18:14.823
That must make you angry.

313
00:18:14.894 --> 00:18:16.886
It bothers me.

314
00:18:16.963 --> 00:18:19.432
It's not really in
Augustine's best interests.

315
00:18:23.102 --> 00:18:26.470
You want some?

316
00:18:26.539 --> 00:18:29.532
I shouldn't.

317
00:18:34.313 --> 00:18:37.374
I guess you gotta be good at reading
people to be a good infirmarian. huh?

318
00:18:37.450 --> 00:18:40.477
Mm. Mm-hmm.

319
00:18:40.553 --> 00:18:43.182
So. we've got pride.
anger. envy. gluttony...

320
00:18:44.557 --> 00:18:47.755
That's four out of seven
deadly sins in under two minutes.

321
00:18:47.827 --> 00:18:50.820
Do you people keep records of
these things? Is there a "Cathlympics"?

322
00:18:52.999 --> 00:18:55.992
They say you have a
gift. <i>They</i> like to talk.

323
00:18:56.068 --> 00:18:59.596
- You hide behind your intelligence.
- Yeah. That's pretty stupid.

324
00:18:59.672 --> 00:19:02.665
And you make jokes because
you're afraid to take anything seriously.

325
00:19:02.742 --> 00:19:05.007
Because if you take
things seriously. they matter.

326
00:19:05.077 --> 00:19:08.172
<i>And if they matter—</i> When
things go wrong. I get hurt.

327
00:19:08.247 --> 00:19:11.342
- I'm not tough. I'm vulnerable.
- I barely know you.

328
00:19:11.417 --> 00:19:14.615
And I don't know if I'm
right. I just hope I am.

329
00:19:14.687 --> 00:19:17.088
Because the alternative is...

330
00:19:17.156 --> 00:19:19.625
<i>you really are as miserable
as you seem to be.</i>

331
00:19:22.528 --> 00:19:25.657
You know. from the way
you're looking at me right now.

332
00:19:25.731 --> 00:19:27.700
I'd say you just
hit number five.

333
00:19:29.035 --> 00:19:31.402
Lust.

334
00:19:43.315 --> 00:19:46.581
<i>[TV Turns On]
Dr. Brown. I love you too.</i>

335
00:19:48.888 --> 00:19:51.756
[Air Hissing]

336
00:19:51.824 --> 00:19:54.055
[Vacuum Releases]

337
00:19:55.127 --> 00:19:58.427
<i>How are you
feeling?</i> A little weak.

338
00:19:58.497 --> 00:20:01.160
- That's from the oxygen.
- My mouth is dry.

339
00:20:01.233 --> 00:20:04.601
<i>Okay. Well. uh. I'll get
you some of your tea.</i>

340
00:20:06.806 --> 00:20:10.607
Mixed connective tissue disease?
Her A.N.A. is barely elevated.

341
00:20:10.676 --> 00:20:13.407
Thanks for checking up on her.
Good to know you got my back.

342
00:20:13.479 --> 00:20:17.143
O₂ sat's down to 83. Pulmonary
problems. breathing problems.

343
00:20:17.216 --> 00:20:19.242
Irritation from the
oxygen is typical.

344
00:20:19.318 --> 00:20:22.220
She comes in with a rash. and
you put her into cardiac arrest.

345
00:20:22.288 --> 00:20:24.450
[Sighs] That well just
never runs dry. does it?

346
00:20:24.523 --> 00:20:28.016
If there was no underlying problem. why
is she still having the rapid heart rate?

347
00:20:28.094 --> 00:20:30.772
<i>Maybe from the herpetic encephalitis
caused by you giving her prednisone.</i>

348
00:20:30.796 --> 00:20:32.992
Her reaction is a
symptom. not an error.

349
00:20:33.065 --> 00:20:35.277
There's always an explanation.
isn't there? Yes. there is.

350
00:20:35.301 --> 00:20:36.616
And if this one
doesn't work. we'll find

351
00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:38.280
another. But never one
involving you screwing up.

352
00:20:38.304 --> 00:20:40.296
One that fits all the facts.

353
00:20:40.372 --> 00:20:43.672
Look. we obviously have a
difference of opinion. and that's fine.

354
00:20:43.743 --> 00:20:45.486
But. unfortunately. I've
used up all the time I

355
00:20:45.510 --> 00:20:47.389
budgeted today for banging
my head against a wall.

356
00:20:47.413 --> 00:20:50.850
I'm gonna do you the biggest
favor one doctor can do for another.

357
00:20:50.916 --> 00:20:53.715
I am gonna stop you
from killing your patient.

358
00:20:53.786 --> 00:20:56.187
You're off the case.

359
00:21:14.473 --> 00:21:16.718
We're gonna treat the symptoms.
Not the underlying condition?

360
00:21:16.742 --> 00:21:19.268
There is no underlying
condition. What's her status?

361
00:21:19.345 --> 00:21:21.405
The sister's
breathing is labored.

362
00:21:21.480 --> 00:21:23.881
Pneumonitis from the
hyperbaric chamber.

363
00:21:23.949 --> 00:21:27.317
<i>Put her on 40% oxygen until her O</i>₂<i>sats
increase.</i> B.U.N. and creatinine's rising.

364
00:21:27.386 --> 00:21:29.946
A.L.T. and A.S.T.
twice the normal range.

365
00:21:30.022 --> 00:21:33.618
Could be from the hypotensive
episode. Let's follow them with labs.

366
00:21:33.692 --> 00:21:37.356
She still has the rash and
joint pain she came in with.

367
00:21:37.429 --> 00:21:39.178
<i>Order a nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory.</i> When we were

368
00:21:39.202 --> 00:21:41.009
looking at the differential
diagnosis with Dr. House.

369
00:21:41.033 --> 00:21:43.935
<i>we were considering—</i> I don't need to
hear what Dr. House was considering.

370
00:21:44.003 --> 00:21:47.440
All of this woman's symptoms can be
traced to Dr. House's considerations.

371
00:21:50.109 --> 00:21:52.044
<i>Okay.</i>

372
00:21:52.111 --> 00:21:54.603
Let's just get this
patient healthy.

373
00:21:54.680 --> 00:21:57.411
I want her going out the
front door and not the back.

374
00:21:59.418 --> 00:22:01.353
Hey. it's not like
I betrayed him.

375
00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:03.932
Cuddy would have found out about
the hyperbaric treatments eventually.

376
00:22:03.956 --> 00:22:06.118
You did what you
thought you had to. [Sighs]

377
00:22:22.575 --> 00:22:24.510
<i>Can't get enough
of this place. huh?</i>

378
00:22:26.312 --> 00:22:28.247
Came for my stethoscope.

379
00:22:28.314 --> 00:22:31.341
So I shouldn't read too much into
the fact that you were looking for it...

380
00:22:31.417 --> 00:22:33.409
in the drawer with the
epinephrine syringes in it?

381
00:22:35.521 --> 00:22:38.582
Okay. Yeah. I'd like
to clear my reputation.

382
00:22:38.657 --> 00:22:42.219
Oh. right. I forgot how much
you care about what people think.

383
00:22:42.294 --> 00:22:45.128
Prescribing cigarettes
for inflammatory bowel?

384
00:22:45.197 --> 00:22:47.291
That's. uh—They cause
lung cancer. you know.

385
00:22:47.366 --> 00:22:50.131
You know why they have
ribbons for breast cancer.

386
00:22:50.202 --> 00:22:53.969
colorectal cancer. prostate
cancer— And not for lung cancer?

387
00:22:54.039 --> 00:22:56.008
They ran out of colors?

388
00:22:56.075 --> 00:22:58.635
It's because people
blame lung cancer patients.

389
00:22:58.711 --> 00:23:00.646
They smoke. They screwed
up. They deserve to die.

390
00:23:00.713 --> 00:23:03.808
The reason people die
from lung cancer is guilt.

391
00:23:03.883 --> 00:23:06.717
Huh. Well. guilt
does a lot of damage.

392
00:23:08.687 --> 00:23:11.054
You said that with
great significance.

393
00:23:11.123 --> 00:23:14.958
You're not here to find your stethoscope.
You're not here to clear your reputation.

394
00:23:15.027 --> 00:23:19.192
<i>You're here because you're having
doubts. You might have screwed up.</i>

395
00:23:19.265 --> 00:23:21.860
I'm here because. if I'm right.
Cuddy is killing that patient.

396
00:23:21.934 --> 00:23:24.301
<i>Okay. But if you’re wrong?</i>

397
00:23:26.772 --> 00:23:28.707
Then she's saving her. <i>Fine.</i>

398
00:23:28.774 --> 00:23:31.219
<i>You're gonna have to go through
every record of every patient...</i>

399
00:23:31.243 --> 00:23:33.735
who's been through this
clinic in the last two days.

400
00:23:33.812 --> 00:23:36.976
And you're gonna have to hope
that those records can be trusted.

401
00:23:37.049 --> 00:23:39.245
Which. by the way. yours can't.

402
00:23:49.962 --> 00:23:53.091
These pills will help your kidneys
function a little better. Sister.

403
00:24:00.105 --> 00:24:02.040
Get your wrist?

404
00:24:03.842 --> 00:24:06.243
What's that?

405
00:24:06.312 --> 00:24:08.679
104.

406
00:24:08.747 --> 00:24:11.740
<i>Is that good?</i> It's fine.

407
00:24:13.018 --> 00:24:16.955
You're a lousy liar.
Dr. Chase. <i>[Pager Beeping]</i>

408
00:24:22.861 --> 00:24:25.695
I have to get this. Excuse me.

409
00:24:25.764 --> 00:24:28.233
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

410
00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.531
My mother's been
dead for 10 years.

411
00:24:31.670 --> 00:24:33.639
But she's always
with you in spirit.

412
00:24:33.706 --> 00:24:35.800
What do you know about
the nun? Which one?

413
00:24:35.874 --> 00:24:39.311
The cute one. I
think she likes me.

414
00:24:39.378 --> 00:24:43.110
- The sick one. obviously.
- Her parents died when she was a child.

415
00:24:43.182 --> 00:24:45.777
<i>She's been with the Church
ever since.</i> What's she lying about?

416
00:24:45.851 --> 00:24:48.320
- Why do you say that?
- I always say that.

417
00:24:48.387 --> 00:24:51.084
And the old nun thinks the
sick nun is a big fat nun liar.

418
00:24:51.156 --> 00:24:53.921
You know nuns. What do
you think? I don't know nuns.

419
00:24:53.993 --> 00:24:56.986
You hate nuns. You can't hate
someone if you don't know them.

420
00:24:57.062 --> 00:24:59.622
Know any Nazis? Maybe
I hate them on principle.

421
00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:03.897
I have a theory about what
makes good boys good.

422
00:25:03.969 --> 00:25:07.303
It's not because of
some moral imperative.

423
00:25:07.373 --> 00:25:09.706
Good boys have the
fear of God put into them.

424
00:25:09.775 --> 00:25:12.836
Catholic Church specializes
in that kind of training...

425
00:25:12.911 --> 00:25:15.904
To make good boys
afraid of divine retribution.

426
00:25:15.981 --> 00:25:18.109
so they'll do what
their daddies tell them...

427
00:25:18.183 --> 00:25:20.228
Like. for example.
going into medical school

428
00:25:20.252 --> 00:25:22.086
when it's the last
thing they wanna do.

429
00:25:22.154 --> 00:25:24.089
What do you think?

430
00:25:25.557 --> 00:25:28.288
I think. if she did have a
secret. her boss would know.

431
00:25:30.863 --> 00:25:33.799
<i>[Bells Tolling]</i>

432
00:25:33.866 --> 00:25:37.359
Did you paint or put in
new carpets recently? No.

433
00:25:37.436 --> 00:25:39.632
Any way she could
have got access to drugs?

434
00:25:39.705 --> 00:25:41.782
We lock all our
medications in the infirmary.

435
00:25:41.806 --> 00:25:43.767
and we don't keep
prescription drugs here.

436
00:25:43.842 --> 00:25:48.109
Why haven't you asked Sister
Augustine about these things directly?

437
00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:51.116
<i>I've found that when you want
to know the truth about someone.</i>

438
00:25:51.183 --> 00:25:53.948
that someone is probably
the last person you should ask.

439
00:25:54.019 --> 00:25:56.648
Ah. And have you been
speaking to Sister Eucharist?

440
00:25:56.722 --> 00:26:00.352
She ratted out her fellow
sister pretty quickly. <i>Oh.</i>

441
00:26:00.426 --> 00:26:02.657
<i>If I were you. I'd have her
repeat a year of nun school.</i>

442
00:26:02.728 --> 00:26:06.062
[Laughing] Well. becoming a
nun doesn't make you a saint.

443
00:26:06.131 --> 00:26:08.566
<i>Becoming a doctor
doesn't make you a healer.</i>

444
00:26:08.634 --> 00:26:12.469
And just because we live in a monastery.
and we spend most of our time in prayer.

445
00:26:12.538 --> 00:26:15.406
doesn't mean we don't
find time for drama.

446
00:26:15.474 --> 00:26:17.340
So. what is the
sick one's drama?

447
00:26:17.409 --> 00:26:22.143
Sister Augustine lived in Catholic
foster care until she came to us.

448
00:26:22.214 --> 00:26:24.149
<i>[Teakettle Whistling]</i>

449
00:26:24.216 --> 00:26:26.913
- Tea?
- Sure.

450
00:26:30.089 --> 00:26:32.718
Do all of you lie?

451
00:26:32.791 --> 00:26:35.370
<i>It's a good strategy; it's simpler
when you all tell the same lie.</i>

452
00:26:35.394 --> 00:26:38.364
She has not spent her
entire life as a good Catholic.

453
00:26:38.430 --> 00:26:42.367
<i>When she had a cardiac arrest. I
had to open her blouse to do C. P. R.</i>

454
00:26:42.434 --> 00:26:45.427
And I learned two things:
nuns can have nice breasts.

455
00:26:45.504 --> 00:26:49.999
<i>and she has a tattoo on
her shoulder— Of a skunk.</i>

456
00:26:50.075 --> 00:26:54.171
<i>Now. maybe it's the
sacred skunk of Joseph.</i>

457
00:26:54.246 --> 00:26:57.512
but. as far as I know. Catholic
foster care and monasteries...

458
00:26:57.583 --> 00:27:00.382
do not keep tattoo
parlors in their refectories.

459
00:27:00.452 --> 00:27:03.149
We consider that
our life begins...

460
00:27:03.222 --> 00:27:05.748
when we put on our
habits and take our vows.

461
00:27:07.459 --> 00:27:11.419
- What happens before then— - Is
irrelevant to you. but it's relevant to me.

462
00:27:15.567 --> 00:27:18.867
Sister Augustine went into foster
care when she was six years old.

463
00:27:18.937 --> 00:27:21.532
but she left when she was 12.

464
00:27:21.607 --> 00:27:24.475
She lived on the streets.
She got into drugs.

465
00:27:25.844 --> 00:27:27.938
When she was 15.
she became pregnant.

466
00:27:28.013 --> 00:27:29.948
Tried to self-abort.

467
00:27:30.015 --> 00:27:32.951
She lost the child.
She became ill.

468
00:27:33.018 --> 00:27:34.953
We took her in
when she came back.

469
00:27:35.020 --> 00:27:39.549
If we had thought it was medically
relevant. we would have told you.

470
00:27:41.627 --> 00:27:43.653
It's not.

471
00:27:51.770 --> 00:27:55.571
This tea is delicious.
Local herbs?

472
00:27:56.575 --> 00:27:59.841
Any change with the medication?
Yes. She's getting worse.

473
00:27:59.912 --> 00:28:03.212
Lung function's deteriorating. B.U.N.
and creatinine continuing to rise.

474
00:28:03.282 --> 00:28:05.774
She's starting to run a fever.
and the rash is spreading.

475
00:28:05.851 --> 00:28:08.129
At this rate. she's not gonna make
Christmas. Maybe House is right.

476
00:28:08.153 --> 00:28:10.532
Maybe there is an underlying
condition that explains the symptoms.

477
00:28:10.556 --> 00:28:13.151
Something we haven't
considered. Like what?

478
00:28:13.225 --> 00:28:15.353
It could be a metabolic
disorder. Specifically?

479
00:28:15.427 --> 00:28:17.362
Might be genetic. Specifically?

480
00:28:17.429 --> 00:28:19.807
I'm just saying— You're just
saying you think House is right.

481
00:28:19.831 --> 00:28:22.357
Might <i>be right.</i> Of
course he might be right.

482
00:28:22.434 --> 00:28:25.268
<i>It might be the hand of God at
work. Don't say it's something else...</i>

483
00:28:25.337 --> 00:28:27.636
<i>unless you've got
something concrete to offer.</i>

484
00:28:29.942 --> 00:28:32.138
What's this. hemlock?

485
00:28:32.211 --> 00:28:35.511
I'm gonna do you the biggest
favor one doctor can do another.

486
00:28:35.581 --> 00:28:37.516
I'm gonna stop you
from killing your patient.

487
00:28:38.884 --> 00:28:40.650
It's figwort tea—
Great for that little

488
00:28:40.674 --> 00:28:42.878
pick-me-up we're all
looking for in the morning.

489
00:28:42.955 --> 00:28:46.551
Opens the lungs. increases the
blood pressure. stimulates the heart.

490
00:28:46.625 --> 00:28:50.528
Unfortunately. if you then get injected
with even .1 c.c. of epinephrine...

491
00:28:50.596 --> 00:28:53.156
Instant cardiac arrest.

492
00:28:54.233 --> 00:28:56.544
- Still. what the hell. it tastes great.
- Sister Augustine...

493
00:28:56.568 --> 00:28:59.060
Has been drinking it
religiously. so to speak.

494
00:28:59.137 --> 00:29:02.130
And if you take the cardiac
arrest out of the equation...

495
00:29:02.207 --> 00:29:04.406
All the rest of the
symptoms can be explained

496
00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:06.406
by a severe long-term
allergic reaction.

497
00:29:06.478 --> 00:29:08.640
Well. that's what Cameron
said in the beginning.

498
00:29:08.714 --> 00:29:12.310
<i>Yes. she did. Well done.</i>

499
00:29:12.384 --> 00:29:17.584
But your unwillingness to stick by
your diagnosis almost killed this woman.

500
00:29:17.656 --> 00:29:20.216
Take a lesson from Foreman—
Stand up for what you believe.

501
00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:25.925
Okay. Let's go figure
out how to save a nun.

502
00:29:25.998 --> 00:29:28.024
Damned if you do.
damned if you don't.

503
00:29:29.501 --> 00:29:31.436
<i>[House] Because it's
been untreated for so long.</i>

504
00:29:31.503 --> 00:29:34.063
it's gone from a simple "watery
eyes. scratchy throat" allergy...

505
00:29:34.106 --> 00:29:36.439
to a whopping "I'm gonna
kick your ass" allergy...

506
00:29:36.508 --> 00:29:38.380
Compromising her immune
system. diminishing her

507
00:29:38.404 --> 00:29:40.502
ability to heal and breaking
down her organ systems.

508
00:29:40.579 --> 00:29:44.016
So. what's the source?
<i>[Chase] The dish soap.</i>

509
00:29:44.082 --> 00:29:47.109
No. The symptoms persisted
days after the dish-washing episode.

510
00:29:47.185 --> 00:29:48.766
It's gotta be something
she's been exposed to

511
00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:50.431
here in the hospital as
well as the monastery.

512
00:29:50.455 --> 00:29:52.617
[Foreman] What about the
tea? It caused her arrhythmia.

513
00:29:52.691 --> 00:29:54.626
Could be. but
it's not definitive.

514
00:29:54.693 --> 00:29:57.538
[Chase] We'll skin-test for allergens.
[Cameron] Not yet. She's too reactive.

515
00:29:57.562 --> 00:29:59.540
She tests positive to everything.
We need to stabilize her...

516
00:29:59.564 --> 00:30:02.659
Isolate her from all possible
allergens— Give her system a rest.

517
00:30:02.734 --> 00:30:04.669
[Chase] Get her in a
clean room. [House] Okay.

518
00:30:04.736 --> 00:30:06.914
Then gradually introduce
allergens and see how she responds.

519
00:30:06.938 --> 00:30:09.806
When she reacts to something.
we'll know that's what's killing her.

520
00:30:11.276 --> 00:30:14.212
There you go. No
television. no books.

521
00:30:14.279 --> 00:30:16.544
- Not even my Bible?
- I'm afraid not.

522
00:30:16.615 --> 00:30:18.982
This room has filtered
air. filtered water.

523
00:30:19.051 --> 00:30:22.920
<i>You even have silk sheets—
Very decadent and hypoallergenic.</i>

524
00:30:22.988 --> 00:30:25.457
You should be
feeling better here.

525
00:30:25.524 --> 00:30:27.891
[Monitor Beeping]

526
00:30:27.959 --> 00:30:31.123
We'll be back to check
on you in a little while.

527
00:30:31.196 --> 00:30:35.395
Can the other sisters
come in and pray with me?

528
00:30:36.668 --> 00:30:39.433
It'd be better if you
don't have any visitors.

529
00:30:39.504 --> 00:30:42.099
Once we isolate what's
causing your allergy.

530
00:30:42.174 --> 00:30:44.109
<i>then we can be
a little more lax.</i>

531
00:30:46.545 --> 00:30:48.480
[Whimpers]

532
00:30:48.547 --> 00:30:51.039
[Crying]

533
00:30:53.885 --> 00:30:57.754
<i>[Whimpering]</i> I-I
can pray with you.

534
00:30:57.823 --> 00:31:00.554
I don't wanna die.

535
00:31:00.625 --> 00:31:02.787
[Crying] Why has he left me?

536
00:31:12.771 --> 00:31:14.797
I was in seminary school.

537
00:31:16.875 --> 00:31:19.140
They asked us once what
our favorite passage was.

538
00:31:19.211 --> 00:31:22.375
I chose First Peter.
chapter one. verse seven.

539
00:31:24.616 --> 00:31:28.451
"These trials only test your faith to
see whether or not it is strong and pure.

540
00:31:28.520 --> 00:31:33.823
Your faith is being tested. as
fire tests gold and purifies it."

541
00:31:33.892 --> 00:31:37.294
"And your faith is far more
precious to the Lord than mere gold.

542
00:31:37.362 --> 00:31:39.695
"So if your faith remains
strong after being tested.

543
00:31:39.765 --> 00:31:44.396
"it will bring you much
praise and glory and honor...

544
00:31:45.871 --> 00:31:47.806
on the day of his return."

545
00:31:47.873 --> 00:31:50.001
He hasn't left you.

546
00:31:50.075 --> 00:31:53.978
[Laughing. Crying]

547
00:31:54.045 --> 00:31:57.072
The only thing in the way of you
knowing he's there is your fear.

548
00:31:57.149 --> 00:32:02.850
You have a choice—faith
or fear. That's the test.

549
00:32:02.921 --> 00:32:05.083
Choosing faith doesn't
mean I won't die.

550
00:32:05.157 --> 00:32:07.319
But it will affect how you
experience your death...

551
00:32:07.392 --> 00:32:09.987
and. therefore. your life.

552
00:32:10.061 --> 00:32:11.825
It's up to you.

553
00:32:11.897 --> 00:32:14.890
Why did you leave
seminary school?

554
00:32:16.635 --> 00:32:19.230
That test.

555
00:32:19.304 --> 00:32:21.899
You passed. I didn't.

556
00:32:23.308 --> 00:32:26.540
We'll call you if anything
changes. Will she be all right?

557
00:32:26.611 --> 00:32:28.623
As long as she's not
exposed to anything that

558
00:32:28.647 --> 00:32:30.548
can aggravate her
allergy. she'll be fine.

559
00:32:31.983 --> 00:32:35.943
- I need some help in here!
- [Sister Augustine Gasping]

560
00:32:38.523 --> 00:32:41.584
Screw the procedure!
She's in anaphylactic shock!

561
00:32:41.660 --> 00:32:43.891
No way. She's in a damn
clean room. You kidding me?

562
00:32:43.962 --> 00:32:45.897
Get in here!

563
00:32:45.964 --> 00:32:50.595
<i>[Chase]. 1 c. c. of epi.
[Foreman] We've got to intubate.</i>

564
00:32:50.669 --> 00:32:53.104
<i>[Cameron] I got it.
Get the ambu bag.</i>

565
00:33:04.850 --> 00:33:07.319
<i>[Sister Augustine Gasps]</i> I'm in.

566
00:33:13.191 --> 00:33:15.456
[Oxygen Pulsing]

567
00:33:16.695 --> 00:33:19.392
<i>[Monitor Beeping]</i>

568
00:33:19.464 --> 00:33:21.956
Breathing's stabilized.

569
00:33:23.335 --> 00:33:25.804
It's a clean room.

570
00:33:33.712 --> 00:33:36.181
<i>[House] How do you get an
allergic reaction in a clean room?</i>

571
00:33:38.116 --> 00:33:42.144
Maybe it was the preservatives
in the I.V.? Checked that.

572
00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:44.780
Latex tubing? Checked
that. Checked everything.

573
00:33:44.856 --> 00:33:49.556
Well. it could be mast cell
leukemia. It can cause anaphylaxis.

574
00:33:49.628 --> 00:33:55.124
<i>I checked the blood levels. and it's not
eosinophilia or idiopathic anaphylaxis.</i>

575
00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:58.329
Maybe it's just divine will.

576
00:33:58.403 --> 00:34:00.895
It's not my will.

577
00:34:05.110 --> 00:34:09.878
You do realize. if you're wrong—
About the big picture. that is...

578
00:34:09.948 --> 00:34:11.883
You're going to burn. right?

579
00:34:11.950 --> 00:34:14.112
What do you want me to
do— Just accept it. pack it in?

580
00:34:14.185 --> 00:34:17.644
Yeah. I want you to accept that
sometimes patients die against all reason.

581
00:34:17.722 --> 00:34:19.657
and sometimes they get
better against all reason.

582
00:34:19.724 --> 00:34:22.216
No. they don't. We just
don't know the reason.

583
00:34:22.294 --> 00:34:24.991
I think the nuns would
agree with you on that.

584
00:34:30.135 --> 00:34:32.229
[Tapping]

585
00:34:34.172 --> 00:34:37.142
I just wanted to say that I know
that you did everything you could.

586
00:34:37.208 --> 00:34:40.542
I don't need verification from you
to know that I'm doing my job well.

587
00:34:40.612 --> 00:34:43.514
That's your problem. not
mine. I was just being nice.

588
00:34:43.582 --> 00:34:46.347
Yeah. well. you don't
need to always do that.

589
00:34:48.820 --> 00:34:50.686
Merry Christmas.

590
00:35:00.298 --> 00:35:03.666
Sister Augustine's
been extubated.

591
00:35:05.971 --> 00:35:09.203
Good. She's requested to
check out. against medical advice.

592
00:35:09.274 --> 00:35:11.209
She wants to go
back to the monastery.

593
00:35:11.276 --> 00:35:13.541
Well. talk her out of it.

594
00:35:13.612 --> 00:35:16.912
I think I may have
talked her into it.

595
00:35:18.950 --> 00:35:21.249
[Sighs]

596
00:35:33.765 --> 00:35:36.098
Room's paid up for
the rest of the week.

597
00:35:37.602 --> 00:35:39.537
<i>Might as well stick around.</i>

598
00:35:39.604 --> 00:35:43.871
This illness... is
a test of my faith.

599
00:35:43.942 --> 00:35:48.141
If it's his will to take me. it
doesn't matter where I am.

600
00:35:48.213 --> 00:35:50.944
<i>I can accept that.</i>

601
00:35:51.016 --> 00:35:53.417
Does anybody believe
anything you say?

602
00:35:55.320 --> 00:35:57.255
You're not accepting.

603
00:35:58.723 --> 00:36:00.658
You're running away.

604
00:36:00.725 --> 00:36:02.887
Just like you always do.

605
00:36:02.961 --> 00:36:05.795
You ran away from the
monastery to get laid.

606
00:36:07.065 --> 00:36:10.866
You ran away from the real world
when getting laid didn't work out so good.

607
00:36:10.935 --> 00:36:14.736
<i>Now things aren't working
out again. so off you go.</i>

608
00:36:14.806 --> 00:36:18.743
Why is it so difficult for
you to believe in God?

609
00:36:18.810 --> 00:36:23.145
What I have difficulty with is
the whole concept of belief.

610
00:36:23.214 --> 00:36:25.683
Faith isn't based on
logic and experience.

611
00:36:25.750 --> 00:36:29.187
<i>I experience God
on a daily basis...</i>

612
00:36:29.254 --> 00:36:33.089
and the miracle
of life all around...

613
00:36:33.158 --> 00:36:37.027
The miracle of birth.
the miracle of love.

614
00:36:37.095 --> 00:36:39.826
He is always with me.

615
00:36:39.898 --> 00:36:44.131
Where is the miracle in
delivering a crack-addicted baby?

616
00:36:44.202 --> 00:36:46.535
Hmm?

617
00:36:46.604 --> 00:36:50.041
Then watching her mother abandon
her 'cause she needs another score.

618
00:36:50.108 --> 00:36:52.236
<i>Miracle of love.</i>

619
00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:55.109
You're over twice
as likely to be killed...

620
00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:58.150
by the person you
love than by a stranger.

621
00:36:58.216 --> 00:37:01.414
Are you trying to talk
me out of my faith?

622
00:37:01.486 --> 00:37:05.321
<i>You can have all the faith you
want in spirits and the afterlife...</i>

623
00:37:05.390 --> 00:37:08.189
and heaven and hell.

624
00:37:08.259 --> 00:37:10.990
But when it comes to
this world. don't be an idiot.

625
00:37:12.163 --> 00:37:15.600
'Cause you can tell me that you put your
faith in God to get you through the day.

626
00:37:15.667 --> 00:37:18.694
but when it comes time to cross
the road. I know you look both ways.

627
00:37:18.770 --> 00:37:23.538
<i>I don't believe he is inside
me and is going to save me.</i>

628
00:37:23.608 --> 00:37:28.342
I believe he is inside
me whether I live or die.

629
00:37:28.413 --> 00:37:30.405
Then you might as well live.

630
00:37:32.350 --> 00:37:34.751
You got a better shot
betting on me than on him.

631
00:37:36.621 --> 00:37:39.318
When I was 15.

632
00:37:39.390 --> 00:37:43.885
I was on every kind of birth
control known to man— [Gasps]

633
00:37:43.962 --> 00:37:47.296
and I still got pregnant.

634
00:37:47.365 --> 00:37:52.269
I blamed God. I hated
him for ruining my life.

635
00:37:52.337 --> 00:37:54.272
<i>But then I realized something.</i>

636
00:37:54.339 --> 00:37:59.971
You can't be angry with God and
not believe in him at the same time.

637
00:38:00.044 --> 00:38:03.776
No one can. Not
even you. Dr. House.

638
00:38:08.953 --> 00:38:12.913
How'd it go? She
has God inside her.

639
00:38:12.991 --> 00:38:16.189
It would have been
easier to deal with a tumor.

640
00:38:16.261 --> 00:38:18.492
Maybe she's allergic to God?

641
00:38:23.501 --> 00:38:26.480
We've looked everywhere for an allergen
that could be causing this reaction...

642
00:38:26.504 --> 00:38:28.598
except one place—inside her.

643
00:38:28.673 --> 00:38:32.041
On her medical history. she didn't
mention any surgery. She had one.

644
00:38:32.110 --> 00:38:35.547
Can we get her records? What hospital was
it at? She didn't have it at a hospital.

645
00:38:35.613 --> 00:38:38.708
Order a full body scan.
What if she refuses?

646
00:38:38.783 --> 00:38:42.311
Tell her I'm looking
for a miracle.

647
00:38:43.454 --> 00:38:46.424
[Foreman] No
piercings. No fillings.

648
00:38:46.491 --> 00:38:50.155
No surgical pins in
the arm. No implants.

649
00:38:50.228 --> 00:38:53.027
It's clean as a whistle.
What's House looking for?

650
00:38:54.599 --> 00:38:58.263
- What is that?
- Don't know.

651
00:38:58.336 --> 00:39:00.931
Lock on it. Get a
3-D representation.

652
00:39:01.005 --> 00:39:03.133
[Typing]

653
00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:08.944
Oh. my God.

654
00:39:11.883 --> 00:39:16.446
The copper cross—a form of birth
control pulled off the market in the '80s.

655
00:39:16.521 --> 00:39:20.219
- So she's allergic to copper.
- Rare. but it happens.

656
00:39:20.291 --> 00:39:22.123
Wouldn't she know
she had an I.U.D.?

657
00:39:22.193 --> 00:39:24.685
She had an abortion.
I.U.D. must have been left in.

658
00:39:24.762 --> 00:39:27.857
embedded in the endometrial
tissue where it couldn't be detected.

659
00:39:27.932 --> 00:39:31.061
So. all we have to do
is remove the I.U.D.

660
00:39:31.135 --> 00:39:33.434
Then the symptoms
should subside.

661
00:39:33.504 --> 00:39:38.204
I got this I.U.D. when I was 15.
It-It's been more than 20 years.

662
00:39:38.276 --> 00:39:41.371
Prolonged exposure to an
allergen with minimal symptoms.

663
00:39:41.446 --> 00:39:45.941
But at some point. all it takes is one last
contact to cause a full-blown reaction.

664
00:39:46.017 --> 00:39:49.351
Just like a balloon filled with
air— One last breath. it explodes.

665
00:39:50.355 --> 00:39:53.723
The first time I got the rash was when
I was washing the copper cookware.

666
00:39:53.791 --> 00:39:58.752
And all your subsequent symptoms
came from ingesting food prepared in it.

667
00:39:58.830 --> 00:40:01.322
Dr. House found his miracle.

668
00:40:01.399 --> 00:40:03.334
I doubt he'll
interpret it that way.

669
00:40:03.401 --> 00:40:05.563
[Laughs]

670
00:40:05.637 --> 00:40:07.663
You told me your
favorite passage.

671
00:40:07.739 --> 00:40:09.731
Would you like to hear mine?

672
00:40:11.976 --> 00:40:14.036
"Celebrate and be glad.

673
00:40:14.112 --> 00:40:17.048
because your brother was
dead and is alive again."

674
00:40:17.115 --> 00:40:20.085
The prodigal son.

675
00:40:20.151 --> 00:40:23.451
He'll be waiting for
you when you're ready.

676
00:40:25.290 --> 00:40:27.521
We'll schedule your
surgery for tomorrow.

677
00:40:34.565 --> 00:40:36.500
The sixth circle of hell.

678
00:40:36.567 --> 00:40:40.299
Confined in a sweat box with a bloody
nose. and all the tissues are soggy.

679
00:40:40.371 --> 00:40:42.636
I think that's the seventh.
No. The seventh is...

680
00:40:42.707 --> 00:40:46.644
God. you must be fun at parties. I
think we both know the flaw in that theory.

681
00:40:46.711 --> 00:40:50.204
How's the sister? Heart rate
is normal. kidneys functioning.

682
00:40:50.281 --> 00:40:51.908
You know how it is
with nuns. You take out

683
00:40:51.932 --> 00:40:53.661
their I.U.D.'s. they
just bounce right back.

684
00:40:53.685 --> 00:40:56.052
Great. Told you
I didn't screw up.

685
00:40:57.689 --> 00:41:00.887
You screwed up. I gave
her .1 c.c. of epinephrine.

686
00:41:00.959 --> 00:41:03.959
Yeah. and if Cuddy hadn't taken you
off the case. you would have killed her.

687
00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:09.000
You wanna come over
for Christmas dinner?

688
00:41:09.067 --> 00:41:12.504
You’re Jewish. Yeah.
Hanukkah dinner.

689
00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:15.335
What do you care? It's
food. It's people. No. thanks.

690
00:41:17.508 --> 00:41:21.946
Maybe I'll come to your place. Your wife
doesn't mind being alone at Christmas?

691
00:41:22.013 --> 00:41:24.778
I'm a doctor. She's
used to being alone.

692
00:41:26.217 --> 00:41:28.277
I don't wanna talk
about it. Neither do I.

693
00:41:33.291 --> 00:41:35.317
You did good with the nun.

694
00:41:35.393 --> 00:41:40.127
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

695
00:41:40.198 --> 00:41:44.329
Merry Christmas.
Dr. House. Dr. Wilson.

696
00:41:45.636 --> 00:41:47.605
Good night.

697
00:41:49.273 --> 00:41:51.799
That was sweet.

698
00:41:51.876 --> 00:41:55.574
<i>♪♪ [Piano: Seasonal]</i>

699
00:41:55.646 --> 00:41:59.276
[No Audible Dialogue
Over Montage]

700
00:42:14.032 --> 00:42:17.093
<i>♪♪ [Continues]</i>

701
00:42:26.577 --> 00:42:29.547
<i>♪♪ [Continues]</i>

702
00:43:14.225 --> 00:43:16.751
♪♪ [Ends]

703
00:43:55.032 --> 00:43:56.295
That's some bad hat. Harry.

703
